Uneonsciously, perhaps, poet-philosopher as he was, Lucretius carne to see in nature a myste- rious, clusine, but all-pervading principle, almost a personality, that presided over being. Before the majesty oi this generative power he paused in awe. For him its range and sweep were sea and earth and sky, wherever living thing might be. Spring was the glad sea- son oi its quickening advent, and all nature owned its genial sway (see l. 21).
